commitResults.messageTitle: Add support for echo in GUI

commitResults.messageBody:
list command is printing all tasks in one line.

list command should print each task at its own line.

Let's use regex and split the long string by ", " so that Printer.java can handle the rest.

Printing tasks in multiple line is preferable over one line for presentation and readability purposes.

One of the overloaded print functions in Ui.java does not have a JavaDoc.

All public methods should have their own JavaDoc describing what they do.

Let's write a JavaDoc for this method.

JavaDoc is essential for code maintenance and communicating purpose to future developers.

commitResults.messageTitle: Redirect I/O to use the new GUI
commitResults.messageBody:
The application uses I/O from System.in and System.out and the new GUI only echos user input from the text box.

The application needs to make use of the I/O from the new GUI.

Let's:
* Create a new PrintStream in JennyBot::getResponse and set Ui.java to use it.
* Run the commands using user input from the text box in JennyBot::getResponse.
* Return the response from the new PrintStream as a String.

Redirection of I/O is much easier than overhauling the entire I/O process.

We do not use assertions to verify assumptions in our codebase.

We must not let certain assumptions for our code run free without
verification.

Let's use assertions to verify certain assumptions we have about our
code we write.

Assertions are suitable for verifying assumptions about Internal
Invariants, Control-Flow Invariants, Pre-conditions, Post-conditions,
and Class Invariants.

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify codebase to adhere to A-CodeQuality
commitResults.messageBody:
Some parts of our codebase does not adhere to code quality guidelines.

Good code quality is essential to ease of readability and future
code maintenance.

Let's rewrite our codebase to fit the following guidelines.
* Be wary when a method is beyond 30 LOC (lines of code).
* If you need more than 3 levels of indentation, you're screwed.
* Avoid complicated expressions.
* Avoid magic numbers.
* Other guidelines at codeQuality.html#code-quality

Production code needs to be of high quality. Given how the world is
becoming increasingly dependent on software, poor quality code is
something no one can afford to tolerate.
